<subSubSection pageId="83" pageNumber="84" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="83.[189,454,809,835]" box="[189,454,809,835]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,454,809,835]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,454,809,835]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">Differential diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="83.[189,1399,856,954]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">
<taxonomicName authority="Barkalov &amp; Ståhls, 2022" authorityName="Barkalov &amp; Ståhls" authorityYear="2022" box="[189,631,856,883]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Cheilosia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pernigra" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Montanocheila">
<emphasis box="[189,304,856,882]" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">Cheilosia</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[324,506,856,882]" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">Montanocheila</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[526,631,857,882]" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">pernigra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[641,736,857,883]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Barkalov &amp; Ståhls" authorityYear="2022" box="[973,1240,856,883]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Cheilosia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevimontana" subGenus="Montanocheila">
<emphasis box="[973,1000,857,883]" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">C.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1018,1051,857,882]" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">M.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[1070,1240,856,882]" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">brevimontana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis box="[1240,1244,856,882]" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">.</emphasis>
It differs by having yellowish pilosity on tarsi, hind femur, ventral part of anepisternum and katepisternum, while 
<taxonomicName authority="Barkalov &amp; Ståhls, 2022" authorityName="Barkalov &amp; Ståhls" authorityYear="2022" box="[189,444,927,954]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Cheilosia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevimontana" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Montanocheila">
<emphasis box="[189,216,928,954]" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">C.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[233,265,928,953]" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">M.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[282,444,927,953]" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">brevimontana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[451,542,928,954]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
has only black pilosity on legs and pleura.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="83" pageNumber="84" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="83.[189,324,993,1019]" box="[189,324,993,1019]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,993,1019]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,993,1019]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="83.[189,1398,1040,1101]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">
The specific epithet is from the Latin ‘ 
<emphasis box="[648,758,1041,1066]" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">per-niger</emphasis>
’, meaning ‘completely black’ and refers to the colour of the species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
